07504nam a22009735i 9789048503681DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20042004ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485036817 a10.1515/97890485036812doi  a(DE-B1597)518154  a(OCoLC)888545476  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1993.5.U65 -- L38 2004eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4304aThe Last Great American Picture Show :bNew Hollywood Cinema in the 1970s /ced. by Thomas Elsaesser, Noel King, Alexander Horwath. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b23 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPart One: Introductions -- tThe Impure Cinema: New Hollywood 1967-1976 -- t"The Last Good Time We Ever Had": Remembering the New Hollywood Cinema -- tAmerican Auteur Cinema: The Last - or First - Picture Show? -- tPart Two: Histories -- tThe Decade When Movies Mattered -- tA Walking Contradiction (Partly Truth and Partly Fiction) -- tThe Exploitation Generation. Or: How Marginal Movies Came in from the Cold -- tNew Hollywood and the Sixties Melting Pot -- tPart Three: People and Places -- tDinosaurs in the Age of the Cinemobile -- t"The Cylinders Were Whispering My Name": The Films of Monte Hellman -- tNashville Contra Jaws, Or "The Imagination of Disaster" Revisited -- tFor Wanda -- tEverybody Knows This Is Nowhere: The Uneasy Ride of Hollywood and Rock -- tAuteurism and War-teurism: Terrence Malick's War Movie -- tPart Four: Critical Debates -- tThe Pathos of Failure: American Films in the 1970s: Notes on the Unmotivated Hero [1975] -- tTrapped in the Affection Image: Hollywood's Post-traumatic Cycle (1970-1976) -- tGrim Fascination: Fingers, James Toback, and 1970s American Cinema -- tAllegories of Post-Fordism in 1970s New Hollywood: Countercultural Combat Films, Conspiracy Thrillers as Genre Recycling -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tPictures (with credits) -- tIndex of Film Titles0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe French Connection, The Last Picture Show, M.A.S.H., Harold and Maude-these are only a few of the iconic films made in the United States during the 1970s. Originally considered a "lost generation," the 1970s are increasingly recognized as a crucial turning point in American filmmaking, and many films from the era have resurfaced from oblivion to become a reference for new directorial talents. The Last Great American Picture Show explores this pivotal era in American film history with a collection of essays by scholars and writers that firmly situates the decade as the time of the emergence of "New Hollywood." Sam Peckinpah, Arthur Penn, Peter Bogdanovich, Monte Hellman, Bob Rafelson, Hal Ashy, Robert Altman, and James Tobac: these legendary directors developed innovative techniques, gritty aesthetics, and a modern sensibility in American film. Here, contributors compellingly argue that the cinema of today's major directors-Steven Spielberg, James Cameron, Quentin Tarantino, Ridley Scott, Robert Zemeckis-could not have come into existence without the groundbreaking works produced by the directors of the 1970s. A wholly engaging and long-overdue investigation of this important era in American film, The Last Great American Picture Show reveals how the films of the 1970s transformed the American social consciousness and influenced filmmaking worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCinematography -- United States -- History. 0aElectronic books. -- local. 0aMotion pictures -- United States -- History. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / G